    "body": "> I was running into this on macOS as well, today.\n> \n> Found the solution, after reading the last comment from [@cyprienflx](https://github.com/cyprienflx) Turns out enabling the \"Set locale as environment variables on startup\" in the Terminal app needs to be enabled:\n> <img alt=\"image\" width=\"316\" src=\"https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/2862815/363435142-e540e4b3-763f-4825-9ff8-de81e62d767c.png?jwt=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..9Kkv2NyMCkx7wizmII3iwd-JMZctB1ui9DrNXbXYI6w\">\n> \n> This option can be found in the Terminal app preferences under Profiles -> Advanced. After enabling the option a restart of the app fixes the wrapping of long commands.\n\nThis isn't working for me. Notice how the command not only overlaps itself, but the characters are not cleared/updated when resizing the terminal, resulting in an awkward display.\n\n> [!NOTE]  \n> GitHub currently is failing to attach images, so I have elected to recreate the appearance of the text below. Line breaks have been added to preserve the formatting as present in the terminal. *No line breaks exist in the original text, with the text treated as one entire line.*\n\n```sh\nemes/WorkSpace/mintChip-OBS/Theme/mintChip.obt\" /Users/asriel/Library/Application\\ Support/obs-studio/themes/min\ntChip.obtSpace/mintChip-OBS/Theme/mintChip.obt\" /Users/asriel/Library/Application\\ Support/obs-studio/themes/min\nln: /Users/asriel/Library/Application Support/obs-studio/themes/mintChip.obt: File exists\n```\n\nThe prompt is entirely missing in this case because the length of the command overlapped it. Resizing the window then *attempted* to wrap the text, but due to the overlapping and the characters not being cleared, it instead ended up like this.\n\nFor clarity sake, this *was* an `ln` command and its output, at some point. I tried adding the following variables into my `.bash_profile`, with no success as well in remedying the issue:\n\n```sh\nexport LANG=\"en_US.UTF-8\"\nexport LC_COLLATE=\"en_US.UTF-8\"\nexport LC_CTYPE=\"en_US.UTF-8\"\nexport LC_MESSAGES=\"en_US.UTF-8\"\nexport LC_MONETARY=\"en_US.UTF-8\"\nexport LC_NUMERIC=\"en_US.UTF-8\"\nexport LC_TIME=\"en_US.UTF-8\"\nexport LC_ALL=\"en_US.UTF-8\"\n```\n\nAdditionally, using the arrow keys to recall commands will sometimes \"restore\" the prompt, but then letters *after* the prompt that do not get \"overwritten\" by new text remain.\n\nHere is, lastly, the output of my `PS1` variable as seen by bash, printed to a text file:\n\n```sh\n\\[\u001b[48;5;0;38;5;197m\\]\\[\u001b[48;5;197;38;5;230m\\]󰀵 asriel \\[\u001b[38;5;208m\\]\\[\u001b[48;5;208;38;5;230m\\]   \\[\u001b[38;5;220m\\]\\[\u001b[48;5;71m\\]\\[\u001b[48;5;30;38;5;71m\\]\\[\u001b[38;5;230m\\]  v19.0.1 \\[\u001b[48;5;55;38;5;30m\\]\\[\u001b[48;5;59;38;5;55m\\]\\[\u001b[48;5;236;38;5;59m\\]\\[\u001b[38;5;230m\\]    14:43   \\[\u001b[48;5;154;38;5;236m\\]\\[\u001b[38;5;0m\\]  \\[\u001b[1;38;5;106m\\]\\[\u001b[48;5;106;38;5;0m\\] \\[\u001b[48;5;0;38;5;106m\\]\\[\u001b[0m\\] \n```\n\n*Seemingly* all the escapes are there. (VSCode counts `18` escapes and `18` instances of `\\]`). So I think there may be more to this issue than meets the eye...\n\n### Environment\n- Starship 1.22.1\n- macOS 15.3\n- Terminal.app\n- GNU bash, version 3.2.57(1)-release (arm64-apple-darwin24)",
